Congenital heart diseases (CHDs), typically defined as structural and functional abnormalities of the heart and great vessels during embryonic development, are the most common type of birth defects. The reported birth prevalence of CHDs varies widely across countries and continents. A recent meta-analysis has estimate that the worldwide prevalence of CHDs in live births increased to 9.41/‰ in the period 2010–2017 [ 1 ]. In China, total CHDs birth prevalence increased continuously, from 0.201‰ in 1980–1984 to 4.905‰ in 2015–2019 [ 2 ]. CHDs are the leading cause of infant morbidity and mortality, and account for approximately 40% of prenatal deaths and 20% of mortality in the first year of life [ 3 ]. Therefore, CHDs place a heavy burden on the healthcare system, and have become a sizable public health concern. The etiology of CHDs is complex and multifactorial. To date,  \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
